Introduction ¶

The main idea behind the proyect is to provide a mean to compare cities based on some specific parameters. Lets say for example that you want to move from one city to the other , and want to live in a neighborhood with some similarities to the one you are currently living. This analisys is based on the assumption that the most important parameters when choosing a neighborhood are schools ,supermarkets, and hospitals as well as the distance to the city center.

Methodology ¶

As stated in the introduction , the main objective of this analysis is to determine wich neighborhoods of th ecity of Cordoba are similar to the one I currently live To do this , firs i need to group the neighborhoods in Rosario using some clustering algorithm , and once i have the model trained , i will do the same with the neighborhoods in cordoba to get wich are similar to mine. The parameter used will be the precense of schools , hospitals and supermarkets as well as the distance to the ciry center. To get this information first i needede to get an aproximate location of the neighborhood center, since the data dont have it . Once this done , will query information about what i need using foursquiare API looking some distance arround the neighborhood center. Since there is no certanty that i will get the same amount of categories in both cities , i need to group them in bigger ones . For example , the category "Secondary school " and "School" both will be part of the "ESCUELA" (SCHOOL) category. The same with the other ones. Finally i will train Kmeans clustering algorithm with the city of Rosario to then use it to cluster Cordoba.

Analysis ¶

In [5]:
#This funcion calculate the aproximate center to a list of 2 dimentional points
def calculateCenter(  points ) :
    longitudes = []
    latitudes = []
    
    for l in points[0]:
        longitudes.append(l[0])
        latitudes.append(l[1])
    latitudes.sort();
    longitudes.sort();
    
    lowX = latitudes[-1];
    highX = latitudes[0];
    lowy = longitudes[0];
    highy = longitudes[-1];
    
    centerX = lowX + ((highX - lowX) / 2);
    centerY = lowy + ((highy - lowy) / 2);

    return(centerX, centerY);
In [6]:
#This function recibes a serie with all the geospatial points , and a list with the names of the neighborhoods and calculate the center of each one
def NombreyCoordenadas(serie,nombres):
    centro=[]
    barrio=[]
    result={}
    for i,s in enumerate(serie):
        #print(s)
        j=json.loads(s)
        lista=j['geometry']['coordinates'] 
        centro.append(calculateCenter(lista))
        barrio.append(nombres[i])
    result['Barrio']=barrio
    result['Coordenadas']=centro
        
    return(pd.DataFrame(result),centro)
In [7]:
#This funcion recibe a lsit of neighborhoods , iths centers  and the center of the city and calculate the distance to the city center. it return a
# dataframe with all this informaiton
def distCentro(barrios,centro,centro_barrio):
    result={}
    distancia=[]
    n=[]
    for i,c in enumerate(centro_barrio.values):
        dist=math.sqrt((centro[0]-c[0])**2+((centro[1]-c[1])**2))
        distancia.append(dist)
        n.append(barrios[i])
        
    result['Barrio']=n
    result['Distancia']=distancia
    
    return(pd.DataFrame(result))

def searchVenues(queries,nombre,latlong):
    #solo busca si le pasas varias coordenadas
    venues_list=[[(np.nan,np.nan,np.nan,np.nan,np.nan,np.nan,np.nan)]]
    CLIENT_ID = 'WBGNJBOCFXD2VRVRQSNSQIDDE4GA0NBUODKSD5Z0BUL42DJ3' # your Foursquare ID
    CLIENT_SECRET = 'I1XABE44UHI3YU5ZXYOBA40BCLYPOIFCCKRLDJCSAZJJXHLE' # your Foursquare Secret
    ACCESS_TOKEN = 'BL1VQW1S4VKNGWGYDBEDFVAHFPANZI2UNVDAPMENLDQKC2IU'
    VERSION = '20180605' # Foursquare API version
    LIMIT = 100 # A default Foursquare API limit value
    radius=300
    for q in queries:
        print(q)
        for n,ll in zip(nombre,latlong) :
        #    print(n,ll)
            url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/search?client_id={}&client_secret={}&ll={},{}&oauth_token={}&v={}&query={}&radius={}&limit={}'.format(CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET, 
            ll[0],
            ll[1],
            ACCESS_TOKEN, 
            VERSION,
            q, 
            radius,
            LIMIT)
            print(url)
            results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['venues']
        # return only relevant information for each nearby venue
        #se rompe si viene vacio
            #print(url)
            for v in results:
                    try:
                        venues_list.append([(
                        n, 
                        ll[0],
                        ll[1],
                        v['name'], 
                        v['location']['lat'], 
                        v['location']['lng'],  
                        v['categories'][0]['name'])])
                        break
                    except IndexError:
                            venues_list.append([(
                        n, 
                        ll[0],
                        ll[1],
                        v['name'], 
                        v['location']['lat'], 
                        v['location']['lng'],  
                        np.nan)])
    nearby_venues = pd.DataFrame([item for venue_list in venues_list for item in venue_list])
    nearby_venues.columns = ['Neighborhood', 
                  'Neighborhood Latitude', 
                  'Neighborhood Longitude', 
                  'Venue', 
                  'Venue Latitude', 
                  'Venue Longitude', 
                  'Venue Category']
    return(nearby_venues)

#This funtion doeas the important part of grouping the catecgories

def correctorCategoria(datos):
    #devuelve el df que deberia ser  barrio,lat barrio, long barrio , venue , venue lat , venue long, venue categoria modificado
    df=datos.copy()
    df.reset_index(drop=True)
    #print(df.head())
    #Primero modifico para tener clara la categoria
    es=['School','school','Colleg','colleg']
    sc=['Store','store','marke','Marke','sho','Sho']
    ho=['Hospita','hospita','Medica','medica']
    for i,row in enumerate(df['Venue Category'].values):
        for e in es:
            if bool(search(e,row)):
                #print(i,e,row)
                df.at[i,'Venue Category',]='ESCUELA'
    for i,row in enumerate(df['Venue Category'].values):           
        for s in sc:
            #print(row,s)
            if s in row:
               
                df.at[i,'Venue Category']='SUPERMERCADO'
    for i,row in enumerate(df['Venue Category'].values):  
        for h in ho:
                if h in row:
                     df.at[i,'Venue Category']='HOSPITAL'
    
    for i,row in enumerate(df['Venue Category'].values):
        if bool(not(search('ESCUELA',row))):
            if bool(not(search('HOSPITAL',row))):
                if bool(not(search('SUPERMERCADO',row))):
                        df.drop(i,inplace=True)
    
                
    return(df)

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import matplotlib
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
from scipy.spatial import distance
In [109]:
#clustering
kmax=15

sse=[]
X=grupped.drop(columns=['Neighborhood', 'Neighborhood Latitude', 'Neighborhood Longitude', 'Venue Latitude', 'Venue Longitude'])
X_normalize=StandardScaler().fit_transform(X)
xtrain,xtest=train_test_split(X_normalize)

for k in range(1,kmax+1):
    KMEAN=KMeans(n_clusters=k).fit(xtrain)
    yhat=KMEAN.predict(xtest)
    centroids = KMEAN.cluster_centers_
    curr_sse = 0
    dist=0
    # calculate square of Euclidean distance of each point from its cluster center and add to current WSS
    for i in range(len(xtest)):
        curr_center = centroids[yhat[i]]
        dist+=(distance.euclidean(xtest[i],curr_center))**2
        #curr_sse += (xtest[i, 0] - curr_center[0]) ** 2 + (xtest[i, 1] - curr_center[1]) ** 2
    sse.append(dist)

#This is a modified version of the previous function since cordoba data is  presented different that rosario data
def NombreyCoordenadas_CBA(serie,nombres):
   #recibe serie con datos json en string yy serie con nombres de lugarews y devuelva DF y centros
    centro=[]
    barrio=[]
    result={}
    for i,s in enumerate(serie):
        #print(s)
        j=json.loads(s)
        lista=j['geometry']['coordinates'][0] # lista con todos los puntos de los barrios 
        #print(lista)
        centro.append(calculateCenter(lista))
        barrio.append(nombres[i])
    result['Barrio']=barrio
    result['Coordenadas']=centro
        
    return(pd.DataFrame(result),centro)

map_clusters_cba = folium.Map(location=centro_cba, zoom_start=11)
kclusters=3
# set color scheme for the clusters
x = np.arange(kclusters)
ys = [i + x + (i*x)**2 for i in range(kclusters)]
colors_array = cm.rainbow(np.linspace(0, 1, len(ys)))
rainbow = [colors.rgb2hex(i) for i in colors_array]

# add markers to the map
markers_colors = []
for lat, lon, poi, cluster in zip(data_final_cordoba['Neighborhood Latitude'], 
                                  data_final_cordoba['Neighborhood Longitude'], 
                                  data_final_cordoba['Neighborhood'],
                                  data_final_cordoba['Cluster Label']):
    label = folium.Popup(str(poi) + ' Cluster ' + str(cluster), parse_html=True)
    folium.CircleMarker(
        [lat, lon],
        radius=8,
        popup=label,
        color=rainbow[cluster-1],
        fill=True,
        fill_color=rainbow[cluster-1],
        fill_opacity=1).add_to(map_clusters_cba)

Results and Discussion ¶

Considering the final objetive that was to know wich neihborhoods of cordoba will be most suitable to live , based in my personals request , the study gave me a good start point. Since i already live in Rosario , particulary in a Green cluster , i can confirm that the clustering sistem works pretty well . This last thing gave me some real wolrd proof that all this methods can be trusted. Im well aware that using more data as for example mean housing price could help me reduce the amount of options in cordoba city , but the reality is that is not easy to get this infomration for those cities.

Conclusion ¶

The main challenge of the proyect was to proceess all the data i got from various sources, since they dont follow the same pattern. This proyect gave me a pseudo-"real life" experience when working with data , starting with an idea and morph it into something concrete. Furthermore i learn a lot about Json , in particular GeoJson and all of its uses, and I think this is a really usefull skill for Data Science
